<h1>Queen Anne's Lace</h1>

<p>
Queen Anne's Lace is a delicate wildflower known for its lacy white umbels and graceful roadside appearance.
</p>

<h2>Description</h2>

<p>
The plant produces flat clusters of tiny white flowers arranged like lace, often with a single dark central floret.
Its foliage is finely divided and fern-like.
</p>

<p>
It is closely related to the cultivated carrot.
</p>

<h2>Taxonomy</h2>

<p>
Queen Anne's Lace belongs to the species <strong>Daucus Carota</strong> in the family <strong>Apiaceae</strong>.
It is the wild ancestor of many domesticated carrots.
</p>

