<h3>Etymology</h3>

<p>
The common name refers to Queen Anne of Great Britain, with legend claiming the flower resembles lacework stained by a drop of blood.
</p>

<h2>Ecology</h2>

<p>
Queen Anne's Lace attracts beneficial insects, bees, butterflies, and predatory wasps in open meadows and roadsides.
</p>

<h3>Diseases and pests</h3>

<ul>
<li>Leaf blight fungal diseases</li>
<li>Aphids on stems</li>
<li>Root rot in saturated soil</li>
<li>Carrot rust fly in related crops</li>
</ul>

<h2>Cultivation</h2>

<p>
It is grown in wildflower gardens and naturalized meadows, though it may spread readily.
</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Light:</strong> Full sun</li>
<li><strong>Soil:</strong> Average, well-drained soil</li>
<li><strong>Water:</strong> Low to moderate</li>
<li><strong>Planting:</strong> Direct sow seed</li>
<li><strong>Maintenance:</strong> Remove seed heads to limit spread</li>
</ul>

<h2>Queen Anne's Lace in culture</h2>

<p>
The flower symbolizes sanctuary, delicacy, and intricate beauty.
</p>

